  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I pay Costa Rican taxes on my foreign income?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Costa Rica uses territorial taxation—income earned from foreign sources isn't taxed locally. Your $3,000+ from foreign employers remains untaxed by Costa Rica. You may still have tax obligations in your home country.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I bring my family on the Digital Nomad Visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Dependents (spouse and children) can be included in your application. The $3,000 income requirement doesn't increase per dependent, but you'll need additional documentation for family members.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work for Costa Rican clients?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Digital Nomad Visa is for remote work with foreign employers. Working for Costa Rican clients or companies requires a different visa/work permit. Some nomads have foreign companies that happen to have Costa Rican customers—consult an immigration lawyer for gray areas.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the internet like in Costa Rica?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Variable. San José and Central Valley have reliable fiber connections. Beach towns vary—some have excellent internet (Santa Teresa, Tamarindo) while others struggle (rural areas). Always verify connectivity before committing to long-term housing.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I convert to permanent residency?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Digital Nomad Visa doesn't directly lead to permanent residency. After 2 years, you'd need to apply through another category (Rentista, Pensionado, or investment). Costa Rica requires 3 years of legal residency before applying for permanent status.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What about the rainy season?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Costa Rica has two seasons: dry (December-April) and green/rainy (May-November). The Pacific coast gets heavy afternoon rains in green season. The Caribbean has different patterns. Many nomads love the green season—fewer tourists, lush landscapes, lower prices.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

